 ('141', '82', '2', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Astor Grand Tasting Wine Event\",\"slug\":\"astor-grand-tasting-wine-event\",\"postDate\":1429021346,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>\\r\\n\\tFor all the New Yorkers out there -- or anyone else who will be in New York city this Saturday, April 18th, do come and check out \\\"Astor\'s Grand Tasting\\\" event, where yours truly \\\"Poggio La Noce\\\" has been invited to participate. \\r\\n\\t<br>\\r\\n\\t It should be a great event, they\'ve invited only artisan winemakers or as they say \\\"foremost artisan winemakers\\\", 13 wineries and will be serving current releases as well as older vintages. And I forgot the best, Enzo will be there to pour our wines!\\r\\n\\t<br>\\r\\n\\t Time 11.00am to 3.00pm. Place Astor Center. <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.astorcenternyc.com\\/winemakers-invitational\\/default.aspx?ref=hp\\\">Astor Center New York City link<\\/a><\\/p><p>\\r\\n\\t<img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/Astor-Wine-Event-NY.jpg#asset:80\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\">\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"25\":\"\",\"2\":\"\"}}', '2015-04-14 14:22:27', '2015-04-14 14:22:27', '22fa269d-1a1b-4bac-9bc4-62df768a7294'),
 ('142', '84', '2', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Decisions, decisions, decisions...\",\"slug\":\"decisions-decisions-decisions\",\"postDate\":1429022052,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Big Day last Thursday... we were tasting and trying to decide on final blends for next fall\'s releases -- which percentages of which grapes we like best for which bottling -- knowing that the possibilities are infinite! It sounds like fun but it\'s actually a difficult exercise and the worst part is that  one has to spit the wine out ! here in the picture the team: Enzo, Valentino our oenologist and Roberto.<img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/Blend-tasting.jpg#asset:83\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\"><\\/p>\",\"25\":\"\",\"2\":\"\"}}', '2015-04-14 14:34:12', '2015-04-14 14:34:12', '73f922a7-bf56-4c9f-a7aa-c3297231b78e'),
 ('143', '88', '2', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Pinko Pallino getting bottled\",\"slug\":\"pinko-pallino-getting-bottled\",\"postDate\":1429023049,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Getting ready for Spring and Summer? so what do we do? Bottle our Ros\\u00e9! Monday morning we bottled Pinko Pallino. Because 2014 was such a difficult year, we ended up with little ros\\u00e9. We stored it in the smaller vat (with the addition of the cooling plate to maintain temperature at below 12 degrees celcius). This year we had a lot of fun making Pinko Pallino because we ended doing a blend of Gigio\' \\\"bled off juice\\\" and early harvest grapes specifically for ros\\u00e9 with its own w<span class=\\\"text_exposed_show\\\">hite wine like Vinification (meaning that you press the bunches right away). Our bottling operation is still artisanal, but it works! Juice flows from the vat to a small filter to the bottling machine into the bottles which then are immediately corked with the remaining air getting pumped out. We then let the bottles rest 24 hours standing up, to allow the corks to expand and after that they\'re moved to our temperature controlled cellar to rest on their sides until we ship out. We did get to taste it though, yum !!!!<\\/span><\\/p><p><span class=\\\"text_exposed_show\\\"><img style=\\\"width: 448px; height: 251.57px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/getting-ready-to-bottle.jpg#asset:85\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\">  <\\/span><\\/p><p><span class=\\\"text_exposed_show\\\"><\\/span><span class=\\\"text_exposed_show\\\"><img style=\\\"width: 335px; height: 188.57px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/enzo-manning-the-bottling-machine.jpg#asset:86\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\">  <img style=\\\"width: 105px; height: 186.77px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/Pinko-Pallino-bottled-and-corked.jpg#asset:87\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\"><\\/span><\\/p>\",\"25\":\"\",\"2\":\"\"}}', '2015-04-14 14:50:49', '2015-04-14 14:50:49', 'd9a67ec2-ba8e-42c6-aeb2-9ae2b3f6af7d'),
 ('144', '84', '2', '1', 'en_us', '2', '', '{\"typeId\":\"2\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Decisions, decisions, decisions... April 9, 2015\",\"slug\":\"decisions-decisions-decisions\",\"postDate\":1429022040,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Big Day last Thursday... we were tasting and trying to decide on final blends for next fall\'s releases -- which percentages of which grapes we like best for which bottling -- knowing that the possibilities are infinite! It sounds like fun but it\'s actually a difficult exercise and the worst part is that  one has to spit the wine out ! here in the picture the team: Enzo, Valentino our oenologist and Roberto.<\\/p><p>                                 <img style=\\\"width: 398px; height: 298.5px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/Blend-tasting.jpg#asset:83:url\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\"><\\/p>\",\"25\":\"\",\"2\":\"\"}}', '2015-04-14 15:09:30', '2015-04-14 15:09:30', '481e9d06-c5a7-4f5e-857a-9828dcbba623'),
 ('145', '88', '2', '1', 'en_us', '2', '', '{\"typeId\":\"2\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Pinko Pallino getting bottled, March 16th, 2015\",\"slug\":\"pinko-pallino-getting-bottled\",\"postDate\":1429023000,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Getting ready for Spring and Summer? so what do we do? Bottle our Ros\\u00e9! Monday morning we bottled Pinko Pallino. Because 2014 was such a difficult year, we ended up with little ros\\u00e9. We stored it in the smaller vat (with the addition of the cooling plate to maintain temperature at below 12 degrees celcius). This year we had a lot of fun making Pinko Pallino because we ended doing a blend of Gigio\' \\\"bled off juice\\\" and early harvest grapes specifically for ros\\u00e9 with its own white wine like Vinification (meaning that you press the bunches right away). Our bottling operation is still artisanal, but it works! Juice flows from the vat to a small filter to the bottling machine into the bottles which then are immediately corked with the remaining air getting pumped out. We then let the bottles rest 24 hours standing up, to allow the corks to expand and after that they\'re moved to our temperature controlled cellar to rest on their sides until we ship out. We did get to taste it though, yum !!!!<\\/p><p><img style=\\\"width: 448px; height: 251.57px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/getting-ready-to-bottle.jpg#asset:85:url\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\">  <\\/p><p><img style=\\\"width: 335px; height: 188.57px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/enzo-manning-the-bottling-machine.jpg#asset:86:url\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\">  <img style=\\\"width: 105px; height: 186.77px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/Pinko-Pallino-bottled-and-corked.jpg#asset:87:url\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\"><\\/p>\",\"25\":\"\",\"2\":\"\"}}', '2015-04-14 15:10:52', '2015-04-14 15:10:52', '0aa768c8-7f49-4443-82e1-37aba393e493'),
 ('146', '88', '2', '1', 'en_us', '3', '', '{\"typeId\":\"2\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Pinko Pallino getting bottled, March 16th, 2015\",\"slug\":\"pinko-pallino-getting-bottled\",\"postDate\":1429023000,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Getting ready for Spring and Summer? so what do we do? Bottle our Ros\\u00e9! Monday morning we bottled Pinko Pallino. Because 2014 was such a difficult year, we ended up with little ros\\u00e9. We stored it in the smaller vat (with the addition of the cooling plate to maintain temperature at below 12 degrees celcius). This year we had a lot of fun making Pinko Pallino because we ended doing a blend of Gigio\' \\\"bled off juice\\\" and early harvest grapes specifically for ros\\u00e9 with its own white wine like Vinification (meaning that you press the bunches right away). Our bottling operation is still artisanal, but it works! Juice flows from the vat to a small filter to the bottling machine into the bottles which then are immediately corked with the remaining air getting pumped out. We then let the bottles rest 24 hours standing up, to allow the corks to expand and after that they\'re moved to our temperature controlled cellar to rest on their sides until we ship out. We did get to taste it though, yum !!!!<\\/p><p><img style=\\\"width: 448px; height: 251.57px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/getting-ready-to-bottle.jpg#asset:85:url\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\">  <\\/p><p><img style=\\\"width: 335px; height: 189.56px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/enzo-manning-the-bottling-machine.jpg#asset:86:url\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\">   <img style=\\\"width: 106px; height: 188.78px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/Pinko-Pallino-bottled-and-corked.jpg#asset:87:url\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\" rel=\\\"width: 106px; height: 188.78px;\\\"><\\/p>\",\"25\":\"\",\"2\":\"\"}}', '2015-04-14 15:12:09', '2015-04-14 15:12:09', '7519e734-fe45-497b-9600-0592a6a9fc55'),
 ('147', '91', '2', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"What to do in the winter in a vineyard? Pruning... Feb, 2015\",\"slug\":\"what-to-do-in-the-winter-in-a-vineyard-pruning-feb-2015\",\"postDate\":1429026668,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p> What do you do in the winter in a vineyard? Prune... here are some pictures from the pruning work underway. We\'re no way finished yet, it\'s quite slow going but ever so important. How we prune now will influence how the vines will grow over time and how the fruit will develop over the next two consecutive years.<\\/p><p><img style=\\\"width: 349px; height: 196.19px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/pruning-small-size.jpg#asset:89\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\">   <img style=\\\"width: 349px; height: 196.08px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/vineyard-in-the-winter-small.jpg#asset:90\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\" rel=\\\"width: 349px; height: 196.08px;\\\"><br><\\/p>\",\"25\":\"\",\"2\":\"\"}}', '2015-04-14 15:51:09', '2015-04-14 15:51:09', '12ce366f-5c65-472d-8d18-a128464a378b'),
 ('148', '92', '2', '1', 'en_us', '1', NULL, '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Sun Valley Anyone? Feb 27th, 2015\",\"slug\":\"sun-valley-anyone-feb-27th-2015\",\"postDate\":null,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"fields\":[]}', '2015-04-14 15:57:34', '2015-04-14 15:57:34', 'ad88d231-a938-4390-93a2-58d8e91cff62'),
 ('149', '95', '2', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"More on pruning, March 8th, 2015\",\"slug\":\"more-on-pruning-march-8th-2015\",\"postDate\":1429028787,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Back to Pruning? couple of weeks ago we mentioned that these cold winter months were spent pruning the vines and yes but today let\'s delve into the world of pruning a bit more: <\\/p><p>Here we have our Teroldego vines which we pruned differently than the Sangiovese. For the Teroldego we used a different pruning technique called Double Guyot.<\\/p><p><img style=\\\"width: 340px; height: 174.08px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/double-guyot-small.jpg#asset:93\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\">     <img style=\\\"width: 312px; height: 174.49px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/dougle-g-terrace-small.jpg#asset:94\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\" rel=\\\"width: 312px; height: 174.49px;\\\"><\\/p><p><span class=\\\"redactor-ie-paste\\\"><br><\\/span><\\/p><p>Basically we prune or train the vines to manage their world, their environment. The different techniques allow us to deal with leaf to fruit ratios, light vs shade, air movement, canopy, disease protection, and of course yield. <\\/p><p> In the bulk of the vineyard where Sangiovese grows we\'re doing \\\"spur pruning\\\" -- simply put the cordon or main branch of the vine has a bunch of spurs (mushroom like bumps) which each generate 2 fruiting canes (the thinner branches which produce th<span class=\\\"text_exposed_show\\\">e grape bunches). When we prune, we cut off completely the fruiting cane furthest away from the spur, and shorten the one closest to the spur, thus allowing next year\'s spur to generate 2 new fruiting canes. well that\'s the theory...<\\/span><\\/p><p> With the Teroldego we did \\\"double guyot\\\" pruning. The main difference with the Guyot system is that it keeps a 2 year old cane to allow it to generate more fruiting canes (and thus potentially yield more fruit). It\'s used for less vigorous vine varieties to help yields. So at pruning, we cut off the 2 year old cane, and at the spur: the cane closest to the cordon is cut above two nodes, while the cane furthest away is shortened -- that cane will become next year\'s two year old cane. Only tweak is us doing \\\"double\\\" or \\\"bilateral\\\" meaning that we allow for two 2 year old canes, one on each side.<\\/p><p> That\'s the world of vine pruning in the winter time at La Noce!<\\/p>\",\"25\":\"\",\"2\":\"\"}}', '2015-04-14 16:26:28', '2015-04-14 16:26:28', 'd851f149-5799-4e13-8e89-c4616727a7d4'),
